Here are the most important and commonly used Git commands, grouped by purpose and easy to memorize:


---

ğŸ”¥ Basic Git Commands

Command	Description

git init	Initialize a new Git repository
git clone <repo-url>	Copy/download a remote repository
git status	Check file changes in working directory
git add <file>	Stage a specific file
git add .	Stage all files
git commit -m "message"	Commit staged changes
git log	View commit history
git diff	Show changes not staged



---

ğŸ” Branching & Merging

Command	Description

git branch	List all branches
git branch <name>	Create a new branch
git checkout <branch>	Switch to a branch
git checkout -b <branch>	Create + switch to new branch
git merge <branch>	Merge branch into current branch
git branch -d <name>	Delete a branch



---

â¬†ï¸ Push & Pull

Command	Description

git remote -v	Show remote URLs
git push	Push changes to remote repo
git push -u origin <branch>	Push new branch
git pull	Fetch + merge from remote
git fetch	Only download changes (no merge)



---

ğŸ› ï¸ Undo / Fix Mistakes

Command	Description

git restore <file>	Restore unstaged changes
git restore --staged <file>	Unstage a file
git reset --hard	Reset everything to last commit
git reset --soft HEAD~1	Undo last commit but keep changes
git revert <commit-id>	Undo a commit safely (creates new commit)



---

ğŸŒ Stashing

Command	Description

git stash	Save changes temporarily
git stash pop	Restore stashed changes
git stash list	Show all stashes



---

ğŸ“¦ Tagging

Command	Description

git tag	List all tags
git tag <tagname>	Create a tag
git push origin <tag>	Push tag to remote



